Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Skarlso/moby/commits/2842639e0e22bc2f91271603fb9990fa2ac8ad2e"},{"sha":"2fea30f14603613b40d8ce37c8ea7951f87abd1b","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"hack: add script to regenerate certificates

Certificates were originally added in c000cb64712349141596318dea2a8de2462c8f81,
but did not include a script to generate them. Current versions of Go expect
certificates to use SAN instead of Common Name fields, so updating the script
to include those;

    x509: certificate relies on legacy Common Name field, use SANs or temporarily
    enable Common Name matching with GODEBUG=x509ignoreCN=0

Some fields were updated to be a bit more descriptive (instead of "replaceme"),
and the `-text` option was used to include a human-readable variant of the
content.

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

[{"sha":"bc3d20633950c6872119b6fcf64b02bfabdac8dc","author":{"name":"Abin Shahab","email":"aa5e48ffaae751ccd8830df151a27b555951f193@linkedin.com"},"message":"Resolves coredump caused by `tf.data.experimental.save` with prefetch

Repeat and prefetch in combination cause the snapshot reader Initialize function to be invoked multiple times.
However, there is nothing to prefetch on the very last iteration. This results in Prefetch issuing a CancelThreads call while the snapshot thread is trying to initialize. See https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/6446dda92eaadf11d22377e2354307642d739d73/tensorflow/core/kernels/data/prefetch_dataset_op.cc#L151

Currently the dataset reference counting is done asymmetrically. The reference increment happens at the end of initialization, where as the reference decrement
happens in a destructor. When prefetch cancels the snapshot thread, it errors out of the initialization function. And stops calling the reference increment. However, the reference decrement happens regardless, as it is in the destructor which always is invoked during cleanup. This results in an attempt to decrement the null dataset pointer, and therefore a segmentation fault.
This is different from all other dataset ops, where the dataset reference increment happens in the constructor and the decrement happens in the destructor, which are symmetric.

The solution to this is to ensure that the dataset reference is always initialized to nullptr, and to check for null when decrementing the dataset reference.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/aws-tensorflow-bot/tensorflow/commits/bc3d20633950c6872119b6fcf64b02bfabdac8dc"},{"sha":"9645ca19de2d4b3bfedf2a2d12aff5ffeac371a5","author":{"name":"Amit Patankar","email":"54954d1c36b37893c31550c40ae6dfce26df7e0a@google.com"},"message":"Fix segfaults in `tf.raw_ops.SparseCountSparseOutput`.

Signed-off-by: Adam Williams <awilliams@mirantis.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bearstech/moby/commits/489f57b877204e9e118c53b5c43f67674786b02a"},{"sha":"2842639e0e22bc2f91271603fb9990fa2ac8ad2e","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/fileutils: TestMatches: remove cases no longer valid for go1.16

These tests were no longer valid on Go 1.16; related to https://tip.golang.org/doc/go1.16#path/filepath

> The Match and Glob functions now return an error if the unmatched part of
> the pattern has a syntax error. Previously, the functions returned early on
> a failed match, and thus did not report any later syntax error in the pattern.

Causing the test to fail:

    === RUN   TestMatches
        fileutils_test.go:388: assertion failed: error is not nil: syntax error in pattern: pattern="a\\" text="a"
    --- FAIL: TestMatches (0.00s)

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bearstech/moby/commits/2842639e0e22bc2f91271603fb9990fa2ac8ad2e"},{"sha":"2fea30f14603613b40d8ce37c8ea7951f87abd1b","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"hack: add script to regenerate certificates

Certificates were originally added in c000cb64712349141596318dea2a8de2462c8f81,
but did not include a script to generate them. Current versions of Go expect
certificates to use SAN instead of Common Name fields, so updating the script
to include those;

    x509: certificate relies on legacy Common Name field, use SANs or temporarily
    enable Common Name matching with GODEBUG=x509ignoreCN=0

Some fields were updated to be a bit more descriptive (instead of "replaceme"),

Targeting Android 12 requires explicit declaration of any referenced
native vendor libraries. Include the necessary tags in a GPU-specific
manifest, such that downstream apps inherit them when adding the GPU
library as a dependency, enabling use of vendor-provided OpenCL libraries.

Note that for apps not targeting Android 12 ("S") explicitly, there
should be no change in behavior (with or without this CL).

Also note that this manifest cannot be used by default for OSS builds,
as it requires AGP 4.2.0; this will be addressed in follow-up work.

Change-Id: I8e5f2c5160ee1038311f2eab9c6d7902dbf9a566","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/3a2a840e083a938a92aab6b80aad0fbe8abce9e5"},{"sha":"9880cab2abd158027179e01e54a6d08aee3ac482","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[SE:GPU] Change code that invokes ptxas to prefer ptxas from PATH rather than from hard-coded locations like /usr/local/cuda.

We determine if a valid ptxas is on PATH by trying to run `ptxas --version`. If that works, use it.

The advantage of looking in PATH first is that users can override the PATH, whereas they may not have control over, say, an old version of CUDA in /usr/local/cuda on a shared machine.

Add caching around code that finds executables. There's no need to access the filesystem repeatedly.

Also lower verbosity of failed Subprocess::Start() calls. With this change, we expect some subprocesses starts to fail, so we don't want to LOG about them.

https://github.com/google/jax/issues/6799

Targeting Android 12 requires explicit declaration of any referenced
native vendor libraries. Include the necessary tags in a GPU-specific
manifest, such that downstream apps inherit them when adding the GPU
library as a dependency, enabling use of vendor-provided OpenCL libraries.

Note that for apps not targeting Android 12 ("S") explicitly, there
should be no change in behavior (with or without this CL).

Also note that this manifest cannot be used by default for OSS builds,
as it requires AGP 4.2.0; this will be addressed in follow-up work.

* Adding functions rbegin() and rend() functions to matrix class.

The functions are copy pated from their counterparts (even though they should probably call the counterparts but this gave me some troube).
They return iterators using std::reverse_iterators

Follow up of an open feature request:
https://github.com/opencv/opencv/issues/4641

* Adding rbegin and rend to Mat_ class with the right parameters so we don't need to repeat the template argument.

Follows what is done for forward iterators

* static cast the vector size (return size_t) to an int (that is required for opencv mat constructor)

Certificates were originally added in c000cb64712349141596318dea2a8de2462c8f81,
but did not include a script to generate them. Current versions of Go expect
certificates to use SAN instead of Common Name fields, so updating the script
to include those;

    x509: certificate relies on legacy Common Name field, use SANs or temporarily
    enable Common Name matching with GODEBUG=x509ignoreCN=0

Some fields were updated to be a bit more descriptive (instead of "replaceme"),
and the `-text` option was used to include a human-readable variant of the
content.

Targeting Android 12 requires explicit declaration of any referenced
native vendor libraries. Include the necessary tags in a GPU-specific
manifest, such that downstream apps inherit them when adding the GPU
library as a dependency, enabling use of vendor-provided OpenCL libraries.

Note that for apps not targeting Android 12 ("S") explicitly, there
should be no change in behavior (with or without this CL).

Also note that this manifest cannot be used by default for OSS builds,
as it requires AGP 4.2.0; this will be addressed in follow-up work.

[{"sha":"115e471515813182b93066f5d0f445f25675f68b","author":{"name":"HattrickGenerator","email":"a7620a44cf7aa0cef4a7cd21c91e2fe85c5d1fe8@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #19967 from HattrickGenerator:master

* Adding functions rbegin() and rend() functions to matrix class.
This is important to be more standard compliant with C++ and an ever increasing number of people using standard algorithms for better code readability- and maintainability.

The functions are copy pated from their counterparts (even though they should probably call the counterparts but this gave me some troube).
They return iterators using std::reverse_iterators

Follow up of an open feature request:
https://github.com/opencv/opencv/issues/4641

* Fix rbegin() and rend() and provide tests for them

* Removing unnecessary whitespaces

* Adding rbegin and rend to Mat_ class with the right parameters so we don't need to repeat the template argument.
An instantiating cv::Mat_<int> for example can call it's rbegin() function and doesn't need rbegin<int>() with this convience addition.

Follows what is done for forward iterators

* static cast the vector size (return size_t) to an int (that is required for opencv mat constructor)

Co-authored-by: Stefan <stefan.gerl@tum.de>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/clunietp/opencv/commits/115e471515813182b93066f5d0f445f25675f68b"}]

Targeting Android 12 requires explicit declaration of any referenced
native vendor libraries. Include the necessary tags in a GPU-specific
manifest, such that downstream apps inherit them when adding the GPU
library as a dependency, enabling use of vendor-provided OpenCL libraries.

Note that for apps not targeting Android 12 ("S") explicitly, there
should be no change in behavior (with or without this CL).

Also note that this manifest cannot be used by default for OSS builds,
as it requires AGP 4.2.0; this will be addressed in follow-up work.

There is a not-insignificant performance overhead for all containers (if
containerd is a child of Docker, which is the current setup) if systemd

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/angelcar/moby/commits/80039b4699e36ceb0eb81109cd1686aaa805c5ec"},{"sha":"7daf2db62a69cb6b341addf94d5da82759d7b6c2","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"systemd: don't limit tasks

Systemd sets a default of 512 tasks, which is far
too low to run many containers.

and above.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/angelcar/moby/commits/7daf2db62a69cb6b341addf94d5da82759d7b6c2"},{"sha":"26eddc16a887e84f31ef540e0568cbb998dfe155","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"systemd: add "Delegate=yes" to docker's service file

We need to add delegate yes to docker's service file so that it can
manage the cgroups of the processes that it launches without systemd
interfering with them and moving the processes after it is reloaded.

       Delegate=
           Turns on delegation of further resource control partitioning to
           processes of the unit. For unprivileged services (i.e. those
           using the User= setting), this allows processes to create a
           subhierarchy beneath its control group path. For privileged
           services and scopes, this ensures the processes will have all
           control group controllers enabled.

This is the proper fix for issue moby/moby#20152

Add schedule hints EARLY_AS_POSSIBLE and LATE_AS_POSSIBLE to custom-calls.
This supports a custom-call case, where a logical operation can be lowered into
two HLOs (e.g., PerformX and PerformXDone). We can utilize this mechanism to
either hide host latencies between the pair of the custom-calls or the two calls

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

Certificates were originally added in c000cb64712349141596318dea2a8de2462c8f81,
but did not include a script to generate them. Current versions of Go expect
certificates to use SAN instead of Common Name fields, so updating the script
to include those;

    x509: certificate relies on legacy Common Name field, use SANs or temporarily
    enable Common Name matching with GODEBUG=x509ignoreCN=0

Some fields were updated to be a bit more descriptive (instead of "replaceme"),
and the `-text` option was used to include a human-readable variant of the
content.

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

These tests were no longer valid on Go 1.16; related to https://tip.golang.org/doc/go1.16#path/filepath

> The Match and Glob functions now return an error if the unmatched part of
> the pattern has a syntax error. Previously, the functions returned early on
> a failed match, and thus did not report any later syntax error in the pattern.

Causing the test to fail:

    === RUN   TestMatches
        fileutils_test.go:388: assertion failed: error is not nil: syntax error in pattern: pattern="a\\" text="a"
    --- FAIL: TestMatches (0.00s)

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/next-stack/moby/commits/2842639e0e22bc2f91271603fb9990fa2ac8ad2e"},{"sha":"2fea30f14603613b40d8ce37c8ea7951f87abd1b","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"hack: add script to regenerate certificates

Certificates were originally added in c000cb64712349141596318dea2a8de2462c8f81,
but did not include a script to generate them. Current versions of Go expect
certificates to use SAN instead of Common Name fields, so updating the script
to include those;

    x509: certificate relies on legacy Common Name field, use SANs or temporarily
    enable Common Name matching with GODEBUG=x509ignoreCN=0

Some fields were updated to be a bit more descriptive (instead of "replaceme"),
and the `-text` option was used to include a human-readable variant of the
content.

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

```
raise RuntimeError('You appear to be running a parameterized test case '

```

Reversing the decorator order results in a different error

```

```

so abandoning that approach and adding a `no_rocm` tag to skip the test completely

The subtest being failing on the ROCm platform is `KPLTest.testTrainAndServe`

The error does not seem to be ROCm specific, and am hoping it will be root-caused and fixed in upstream.

[{"sha":"e2f1b934b554c718bca5a96d1b944850bc8830aa","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Get rid of explicit D2H copies in GPU NMS implementation.

Instead, have the GPU write directly to pinned CPU memory.

The GPU can do only one D2H memcopy at once.  If there is already a D2H memcopy
running, we have to wait until it's complete before we can do the one here.

But if we write directly to pinned memory, we don't have this problem.

We've observed this technique elsewhere lead to large latency reductions in
contended cases.

1) Previously, function `GetResourceIdsByValue` filtered out all values that are
   not a `ResourceType` (resource variables), even when they have side-effects.
   Such values were wrongly handled as "known resources" which led to missing
   control dependencies in `BreakUpIsland` pass.
2) Added a test catching this case.
3) Added a test for a common sequence of ops using the `DatasetIterator`
   resource which was not tested before.
4) Improved naming for better readability (the term `resource` is overloaded
   with different meanings).

Targeting Android 12 requires explicit declaration of any referenced
native vendor libraries. Include the necessary tags in a GPU-specific
manifest, such that downstream apps inherit them when adding the GPU
library as a dependency, enabling use of vendor-provided OpenCL libraries.

Note that for apps not targeting Android 12 ("S") explicitly, there
should be no change in behavior (with or without this CL).

Also note that this manifest cannot be used by default for OSS builds,
as it requires AGP 4.2.0; this will be addressed in follow-up work.

Targeting Android 12 requires explicit declaration of any referenced
native vendor libraries. Include the necessary tags in a GPU-specific
manifest, such that downstream apps inherit them when adding the GPU
library as a dependency, enabling use of vendor-provided OpenCL libraries.

Note that for apps not targeting Android 12 ("S") explicitly, there
should be no change in behavior (with or without this CL).

Also note that this manifest cannot be used by default for OSS builds,
as it requires AGP 4.2.0; this will be addressed in follow-up work.

This is a CUDA specific test, and should not be enabled on the ROCm platform","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/25d3a3e4e033886fdae95f8b4e5f4bb7fb0e75a3"},{"sha":"1fc1d59b7310a135082d50b9b84c1a8e79438f41","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"ROCM specific workaround for an MLIR unittest that results in a call to `ThenBlasGemmWithAlgorithm`

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

```
...

2021-04-14 23:22:14.718504: I tensorflow/compiler/xla/service/gpu/gemm_thunk.cc:179] Executing a GemmThunk
2021-04-14 23:22:14.718541: I tensorflow/stream_executor/stream.cc:3487] [stream=0x5597e86929e0,impl=0x5597e868b170] Called Stream::ThenBlasGemmWithAlgorithm(transa=NoTranspose, transb=NoTranspose, m=2, n=2, k=2, alpha=1, a=0x7fe5d4201000, lda=2, b=0x7fe5d4200000, ldb=2, beta=0, c=0x7fe5d420d000, ldc=2, computation_type=f32, algorithm=7)
2021-04-14 23:22:14.718555: I tensorflow/stream_executor/plugin_registry.cc:246] Selecting default BLAS plugin, rocBLAS
2021-04-14 23:22:14.747078: I tensorflow/stream_executor/platform/default/dso_loader.cc:53] Successfully opened dynamic library librocblas.so
2021-04-14 23:22:14.747200: E tensorflow/stream_executor/rocm/rocm_blas.cc:1883] rocBLAS does not currently support the GEMMwithAlgorithm operation for the "float" datatype

This commit updates the code in `gemm_thunk.cc` to always skip the path that calls `ThenBlasGemmWithAlgorithm` routine on the ROCm platform.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/1fc1d59b7310a135082d50b9b84c1a8e79438f41"},{"sha":"c1236b11a872f5a6b9c9696963e9d2465010c368","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Skipping unit-tests (within `segment_reduction_ops_deterministic_test_gpu`) that test complex types.

Initial attempt was to just skip the failing subtest (using the `test.disable_with_predicate` decorator), but that causes the following failure in non-ROCm builds

```
raise RuntimeError('You appear to be running a parameterized test case '
RuntimeError: You appear to be running a parameterized test case without having inherited from parameterized.TestCase. This is bad because none of your test cases are actually being run. You may also be using another decorator before the parameterized one, in which case you should reverse the order.
```

[{"sha":"9880cab2abd158027179e01e54a6d08aee3ac482","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[SE:GPU] Change code that invokes ptxas to prefer ptxas from PATH rather than from hard-coded locations like /usr/local/cuda.

We determine if a valid ptxas is on PATH by trying to run `ptxas --version`. If that works, use it.

The advantage of looking in PATH first is that users can override the PATH, whereas they may not have control over, say, an old version of CUDA in /usr/local/cuda on a shared machine.

Add caching around code that finds executables. There's no need to access the filesystem repeatedly.

Also lower verbosity of failed Subprocess::Start() calls. With this change, we expect some subprocesses starts to fail, so we don't want to LOG about them.

the distinction between 'framework' and 'framework_lib' and make 'framework_lib'

'framework_experimental' (and likewise for 'cc_api').

[{"sha":"6b924bda162118c434efd56d8216b73f10dac11c","author":{"name":"Michael Gester","email":"83d127f0cbc4af4bb827dac2517a3f01bb4703b7@google.com"},"message":"Fix unhandled unknown resources in side-effect analysis

1) Previously, function `GetResourceIdsByValue` filtered out all values that are
   not a `ResourceType` (resource variables), even when they have side-effects.
   Such values were wrongly handled as "known resources" which led to missing
   control dependencies in `BreakUpIsland` pass.
2) Added a test catching this case.
3) Added a test for a common sequence of ops using the `DatasetIterator`
   resource which was not tested before.
4) Improved naming for better readability (the term `resource` is overloaded
   with different meanings).

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

[{"sha":"0b36c628ec83d6d16230ffebcb287a9ab4a4b896","author":{"name":"Mihai Maruseac","email":"d291bc4e1ca4e2dccadea653e3e3371be2da8b06@google.com"},"message":"Remove `OP_REQUIRES` call from helper function.

Since `OP_REQUIRES` macro expands to a `return;` (among other), calling it in a helper function only ends the helper function's execution earlier, but the kernel will still run from start to end. Thus, all the expected validations are actually broken/useless as the code ploughs through the next crash anyway.

Targeting Android 12 requires explicit declaration of any referenced
native vendor libraries. Include the necessary tags in a GPU-specific
manifest, such that downstream apps inherit them when adding the GPU
library as a dependency, enabling use of vendor-provided OpenCL libraries.

Note that for apps not targeting Android 12 ("S") explicitly, there
should be no change in behavior (with or without this CL).

Also note that this manifest cannot be used by default for OSS builds,
as it requires AGP 4.2.0; this will be addressed in follow-up work.

* Adding functions rbegin() and rend() functions to matrix class.
This is important to be more standard compliant with C++ and an ever increasing number of people using standard algorithms for better code readability- and maintainability.

The functions are copy pated from their counterparts (even though they should probably call the counterparts but this gave me some troube).
They return iterators using std::reverse_iterators

Follow up of an open feature request:
https://github.com/opencv/opencv/issues/4641

* Fix rbegin() and rend() and provide tests for them

* Removing unnecessary whitespaces

* Adding rbegin and rend to Mat_ class with the right parameters so we don't need to repeat the template argument.
An instantiating cv::Mat_<int> for example can call it's rbegin() function and doesn't need rbegin<int>() with this convience addition.

Follows what is done for forward iterators

* static cast the vector size (return size_t) to an int (that is required for opencv mat constructor)

ROCm platform does not yet have autotuning support for rocBLAS GEMM API. The `GemmAlgorithmPicker` pass is not called on the ROCm platform ( `amdgpu_compiler.cc` ), so the algorithm field does not get populated, and hence the `ThenBlassGemmWithAlgorithm` routine does not get called.

However the MLIR unit-tests introduced by the following commit ( https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/15e1036cde38ccc5e643b70cc9ecf1c12b3ed931) has the algorithm field pre-populated leading to failure on the ROCm platform

* Adding functions rbegin() and rend() functions to matrix class.
This is important to be more standard compliant with C++ and an ever increasing number of people using standard algorithms for better code readability- and maintainability.

The functions are copy pated from their counterparts (even though they should probably call the counterparts but this gave me some troube).
They return iterators using std::reverse_iterators

Follow up of an open feature request:
https://github.com/opencv/opencv/issues/4641

An instantiating cv::Mat_<int> for example can call it's rbegin() function and doesn't need rbegin<int>() with this convience addition.

Follows what is done for forward iterators

* static cast the vector size (return size_t) to an int (that is required for opencv mat constructor)

The functions are copy pated from their counterparts (even though they should probably call the counterparts but this gave me some troube).
They return iterators using std::reverse_iterators

Follow up of an open feature request:
https://github.com/opencv/opencv/issues/4641

* Removing unnecessary whitespaces

* Adding rbegin and rend to Mat_ class with the right parameters so we don't need to repeat the template argument.

* static cast the vector size (return size_t) to an int (that is required for opencv mat constructor)

[{"sha":"b6fcb7732e0704c2f9895ff0a7e9f6c628c14f71","author":{"name":"Fergus Henderson","email":"f0ea4d8809145d4adcbe42010b047377f121dc12@google.com"},"message":"Split 'framework' target into 'framework_stable' and 'framework_experimental'.
Likewise split 'cc_api' target into 'cc_api_stable' and 'cc_api_experimental'.

Rather than also doing the same for 'framework_lib', instead just eliminate
the distinction between 'framework' and 'framework_lib' and make 'framework_lib'
just an alias for 'framework'.

Move the definitions of experimental methods in interpreter.cc into a new
file interpreter_experimental.cc that is only included in the *_experimental
targets, not in the *_stable targets.  Likewise move experimental methods
in interpreter_builder.cc into a new file interpreter_builder_experimental.cc.

For backwards compatibility, 'framework' is now defined as an alias for
'framework_experimental' (and likewise for 'cc_api').

* Adding functions rbegin() and rend() functions to matrix class.
This is important to be more standard compliant with C++ and an ever increasing number of people using standard algorithms for better code readability- and maintainability.

The functions are copy pated from their counterparts (even though they should probably call the counterparts but this gave me some troube).
They return iterators using std::reverse_iterators

Follow up of an open feature request:
https://github.com/opencv/opencv/issues/4641

* Fix rbegin() and rend() and provide tests for them

* Removing unnecessary whitespaces

* Adding rbegin and rend to Mat_ class with the right parameters so we don't need to repeat the template argument.
An instantiating cv::Mat_<int> for example can call it's rbegin() function and doesn't need rbegin<int>() with this convience addition.

Follows what is done for forward iterators

* static cast the vector size (return size_t) to an int (that is required for opencv mat constructor)

Rather than also doing the same for 'framework_lib', instead just eliminate
the distinction between 'framework' and 'framework_lib' and make 'framework_lib'

Move the definitions of experimental methods in interpreter.cc into a new
file interpreter_experimental.cc that is only included in the *_experimental
targets, not in the *_stable targets.  Likewise move experimental methods
in interpreter_builder.cc into a new file interpreter_builder_experimental.cc.

For backwards compatibility, 'framework' is now defined as an alias for
'framework_experimental' (and likewise for 'cc_api').

Likewise split 'cc_api' target into 'cc_api_stable' and 'cc_api_experimental'.

Rather than also doing the same for 'framework_lib', instead just eliminate
the distinction between 'framework' and 'framework_lib' and make 'framework_lib'
just an alias for 'framework'.

Move the definitions of experimental methods in interpreter.cc into a new
file interpreter_experimental.cc that is only included in the *_experimental
targets, not in the *_stable targets.  Likewise move experimental methods
in interpreter_builder.cc into a new file interpreter_builder_experimental.cc.

For backwards compatibility, 'framework' is now defined as an alias for
'framework_experimental' (and likewise for 'cc_api').

Change-Id: I8e5f2c5160ee1038311f2eab9c6d7902dbf9a566","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/3a2a840e083a938a92aab6b80aad0fbe8abce9e5"},{"sha":"9880cab2abd158027179e01e54a6d08aee3ac482","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[SE:GPU] Change code that invokes ptxas to prefer ptxas from PATH rather than from hard-coded locations like /usr/local/cuda.

We determine if a valid ptxas is on PATH by trying to run `ptxas --version`. If that works, use it.

The advantage of looking in PATH first is that users can override the PATH, whereas they may not have control over, say, an old version of CUDA in /usr/local/cuda on a shared machine.

Add caching around code that finds executables. There's no need to access the filesystem repeatedly.

Also lower verbosity of failed Subprocess::Start() calls. With this change, we expect some subprocesses starts to fail, so we don't want to LOG about them.

https://github.com/google/jax/issues/6799

Likewise split 'cc_api' target into 'cc_api_stable' and 'cc_api_experimental'.

Rather than also doing the same for 'framework_lib', instead just eliminate
the distinction between 'framework' and 'framework_lib' and make 'framework_lib'
just an alias for 'framework'.

Move the definitions of experimental methods in interpreter.cc into a new
file interpreter_experimental.cc that is only included in the *_experimental
targets, not in the *_stable targets.  Likewise move experimental methods
in interpreter_builder.cc into a new file interpreter_builder_experimental.cc.

For backwards compatibility, 'framework' is now defined as an alias for
'framework_experimental' (and likewise for 'cc_api').

Change-Id: I8e5f2c5160ee1038311f2eab9c6d7902dbf9a566","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/guyuchao3/tensorflow/commits/3a2a840e083a938a92aab6b80aad0fbe8abce9e5"},{"sha":"9880cab2abd158027179e01e54a6d08aee3ac482","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[SE:GPU] Change code that invokes ptxas to prefer ptxas from PATH rather than from hard-coded locations like /usr/local/cuda.

We determine if a valid ptxas is on PATH by trying to run `ptxas --version`. If that works, use it.

The advantage of looking in PATH first is that users can override the PATH, whereas they may not have control over, say, an old version of CUDA in /usr/local/cuda on a shared machine.

Add caching around code that finds executables. There's no need to access the filesystem repeatedly.

Also lower verbosity of failed Subprocess::Start() calls. With this change, we expect some subprocesses starts to fail, so we don't want to LOG about them.

https://github.com/google/jax/issues/6799

Likewise split 'cc_api' target into 'cc_api_stable' and 'cc_api_experimental'.

Rather than also doing the same for 'framework_lib', instead just eliminate
the distinction between 'framework' and 'framework_lib' and make 'framework_lib'
just an alias for 'framework'.

Move the definitions of experimental methods in interpreter.cc into a new
file interpreter_experimental.cc that is only included in the *_experimental
targets, not in the *_stable targets.  Likewise move experimental methods
in interpreter_builder.cc into a new file interpreter_builder_experimental.cc.

For backwards compatibility, 'framework' is now defined as an alias for
'framework_experimental' (and likewise for 'cc_api').

Likewise split 'cc_api' target into 'cc_api_stable' and 'cc_api_experimental'.

Rather than also doing the same for 'framework_lib', instead just eliminate
the distinction between 'framework' and 'framework_lib' and make 'framework_lib'
just an alias for 'framework'.

Move the definitions of experimental methods in interpreter.cc into a new
file interpreter_experimental.cc that is only included in the *_experimental
targets, not in the *_stable targets.  Likewise move experimental methods
in interpreter_builder.cc into a new file interpreter_builder_experimental.cc.

For backwards compatibility, 'framework' is now defined as an alias for
'framework_experimental' (and likewise for 'cc_api').

Likewise split 'cc_api' target into 'cc_api_stable' and 'cc_api_experimental'.

Rather than also doing the same for 'framework_lib', instead just eliminate
the distinction between 'framework' and 'framework_lib' and make 'framework_lib'
just an alias for 'framework'.

Move the definitions of experimental methods in interpreter.cc into a new
file interpreter_experimental.cc that is only included in the *_experimental
targets, not in the *_stable targets.  Likewise move experimental methods
in interpreter_builder.cc into a new file interpreter_builder_experimental.cc.

For backwards compatibility, 'framework' is now defined as an alias for
'framework_experimental' (and likewise for 'cc_api').

Co-authored-by: Meng Zhang <mnzhang@mnzhang-mn2.linkedin.biz>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiajunwang/helix/commits/b12e0257f8d819ec3e7759c516f3173c729ab22f"},{"sha":"363f6a4a7a021fc7f9bf2c63ec0fdb3f01f5849f","author":{"name":"Jiajun Wang","email":"9aafcb59640c5ea54c57c4c0f0b46ed999af8e22@linkedin.com"},"message":"Remove a potential deadlock when shutting down a RoutingTableProvider.

This PR aims to avoid a potential deadlock that happens in a race condition when shutting down RoutingTableProvider.

The race condition happens when the RoutingTableProvider is shutdown and the corresponding HelixManager is processing an onLiveInstanceChange event. Both threads require 2 locks, HelixManager lock and RoutingTableProvider._lastSeenSessions, in different orders.
To resolve this problem, this PR changes 2 logics.
1. Remove the _lastSeenSessions lock usage. So no more deadlock. The logic correctness is now ensured by the AtomicReference.getAndSet method.
2. Remove LiveInstanceChangeListener in the shutdown call before processing the other logics. This is a missing logic and should be done regardless of the deadlock problem.Moreover, this change also avoids a more complicated race condition introduced by the previous change that may lead to CurrentStates callback handler leakage.

Test cases in TestZkCallbackHandlerLeak has been updated to validate the logic changes.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiajunwang/helix/commits/363f6a4a7a021fc7f9bf2c63ec0fdb3f01f5849f"}]

We determine if a valid ptxas is on PATH by trying to run `ptxas --version`. If that works, use it.

The advantage of looking in PATH first is that users can override the PATH, whereas they may not have control over, say, an old version of CUDA in /usr/local/cuda on a shared machine.

Add caching around code that finds executables. There's no need to access the filesystem repeatedly.

Also lower verbosity of failed Subprocess::Start() calls. With this change, we expect some subprocesses starts to fail, so we don't want to LOG about them.

https://github.com/google/jax/issues/6799

Add schedule hints EARLY_AS_POSSIBLE and LATE_AS_POSSIBLE to custom-calls.
This supports a custom-call case, where a logical operation can be lowered into
two HLOs (e.g., PerformX and PerformXDone). We can utilize this mechanism to
either hide host latencies between the pair of the custom-calls or the two calls
can more accurately identify the def-use relationship (typically PerformX is
scheduled right after all of its producers have been scheduled and PerformXDone
is scheduled right before its first consumer.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/clayne/tensorflow/commits/7de009c346cd7c67b51fce3c87e855e4f5e3d1be"}]

[{"sha":"7151a6a5663be4851a86f82eecf66a4c4f209832","author":{"name":"Jiajun Wang","email":"9aafcb59640c5ea54c57c4c0f0b46ed999af8e22@linkedin.com"},"message":"Remove a potential deadlock when shutting down a RoutingTableProvider.

This PR aims to avoid a potential deadlock that happens in a race condition when shutting down RoutingTableProvider.

The race condition happens when the RoutingTableProvider is shutdown and the corresponding HelixManager is processing an onLiveInstanceChange event. Both threads require 2 locks, HelixManager lock and RoutingTableProvider._lastSeenSessions, in different orders.
To resolve this problem, this PR changes 2 logics.
1. Remove the _lastSeenSessions lock usage. So no more deadlock. The logic correctness is now ensured by the AtomicReference.getAndSet method.
2. Remove LiveInstanceChangeListener in the shutdown call before processing the other logics. This is a missing logic and should be done regardless of the deadlock problem.Moreover, this change also avoids a more complicated race condition introduced by the previous change that may lead to CurrentStates callback handler leakage.

Test cases in TestZkCallbackHandlerLeak has been updated to validate the logic changes.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiajunwang/helix/commits/7151a6a5663be4851a86f82eecf66a4c4f209832"}]

Likewise split 'cc_api' target into 'cc_api_stable' and 'cc_api_experimental'.

Rather than also doing the same for 'framework_lib', instead just eliminate
the distinction between 'framework' and 'framework_lib' and make 'framework_lib'
just an alias for 'framework'.

Move the definitions of experimental methods in interpreter.cc into a new
file interpreter_experimental.cc that is only included in the *_experimental
targets, not in the *_stable targets.  Likewise move experimental methods
in interpreter_builder.cc into a new file interpreter_builder_experimental.cc.

For backwards compatibility, 'framework' is now defined as an alias for
'framework_experimental' (and likewise for 'cc_api').

We determine if a valid ptxas is on PATH by trying to run `ptxas --version`. If that works, use it.

The advantage of looking in PATH first is that users can override the PATH, whereas they may not have control over, say, an old version of CUDA in /usr/local/cuda on a shared machine.

Add caching around code that finds executables. There's no need to access the filesystem repeatedly.

Also lower verbosity of failed Subprocess::Start() calls. With this change, we expect some subprocesses starts to fail, so we don't want to LOG about them.

Change-Id: I8e5f2c5160ee1038311f2eab9c6d7902dbf9a566","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/PowerOlive/tensorflow/commits/3a2a840e083a938a92aab6b80aad0fbe8abce9e5"},{"sha":"9880cab2abd158027179e01e54a6d08aee3ac482","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[SE:GPU] Change code that invokes ptxas to prefer ptxas from PATH rather than from hard-coded locations like /usr/local/cuda.

We determine if a valid ptxas is on PATH by trying to run `ptxas --version`. If that works, use it.

The advantage of looking in PATH first is that users can override the PATH, whereas they may not have control over, say, an old version of CUDA in /usr/local/cuda on a shared machine.

Add caching around code that finds executables. There's no need to access the filesystem repeatedly.

Also lower verbosity of failed Subprocess::Start() calls. With this change, we expect some subprocesses starts to fail, so we don't want to LOG about them.

https://github.com/google/jax/issues/6799

Likewise split 'cc_api' target into 'cc_api_stable' and 'cc_api_experimental'.

Rather than also doing the same for 'framework_lib', instead just eliminate
the distinction between 'framework' and 'framework_lib' and make 'framework_lib'
just an alias for 'framework'.

Move the definitions of experimental methods in interpreter.cc into a new
file interpreter_experimental.cc that is only included in the *_experimental
targets, not in the *_stable targets.  Likewise move experimental methods
in interpreter_builder.cc into a new file interpreter_builder_experimental.cc.

For backwards compatibility, 'framework' is now defined as an alias for
'framework_experimental' (and likewise for 'cc_api').
